[2] Turkey - vaccinations
Date: Wed 11 Jan 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L11587931.htm>

Turkey should consider vaccines in bird flu fight
-----------------------------------------------
Turkey should consider poultry vaccination in addition to culling to
control its bird flu outbreak if the number of cases in animals
continues to rise, the head of the world animal health body (OIE)
said on Wednesday [11 Jan 2006]. "They must act quickly as soon as
new cases emerge to stamp out the virus. The problem now is that
there are cases throughout the country," OIE Director General Bernard
Vallat told Reuters in an interview. "If cases continue to come to
light, the 2nd option is to use vaccination in the area around
detected outbreaks. Of course, sick animals must still be culled," he
added. "The idea is that you create a protective area around an
outbreak through vaccination. This could involve an entire province,"
Vallat said.
The international community should provide logistical support and
vaccine stocks if Turkey took this option.
The outbreak of H5N1 avian influenza, which has already spread to a
3rd of the country's provinces, has killed at least 2 children and
infected more than a dozen people. Health experts in Turkey have said
there is no sign so far of human-to-human transmission.
The United Nations' Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said on
Wednesday [11 Jan 2006] the virus could become endemic in Turkey and
poses a serious risk to neighboring countries. More than 300 000
birds have been culled since 26 Dec 2005.
Vallat said it was likely that the virus had been around in poultry
flocks for a couple of months in the east of the country, where the
remoteness of the region and harsh weather had hampered efforts to
control it. "We think it was introduced around the same time as the
cases found in October [2005] in the west of the country. But given
the geographical location, detection was later," he said.
In addition, human contact with sick birds had been increased by
people bringing chickens inside their homes due to the low
temperatures, Vallat added. At temperatures of 4 C (39 F) and below,
it could exist in the environment for a month, he said. "This has
allowed it to spread among animals," he said. He also said
neighboring countries such as Iran needed to be on alert for the
appearance of the virus, but as in Turkey, the remoteness of the
region near the border could hamper efforts to detect and control any
outbreaks.
[Byline: David Evans]
