[4] Turkey
Date: Tue 10 Jan 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: AFP [edited]
<http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20060110/hl_afp/healthfluturkey_060110184331;_ylt=AjisYZfBBTVj6VgnZ_GU5MeTvyIi;_ylu=X3oDMTBiMW04NW9mBHNlYwMlJVRPUCUl>

Turkey says bird flu outbreak under control as new human case emerges.
-----------------------------------------------
The Turkish health ministry said the new bird flu case in Turkey was
detected in a patient in the central city of Sivas. It was the only
test of the 61 carried out across the country to produce a positive
result for H5N1. A ministry official told AFP on condition of
anonymity that the patient was carrying the same H5N1 strain that has
killed more than 70 people in Southeast Asia and China since 2003,
before spreading west toward Europe. She is only the 2nd adult among
the 13 cases confirmed so far, the rest being children and teenagers
from several provinces under treatment in hospitals in Ankara, the
northern city of Samsun, and in Van in the east.
The Agriculture ministry said in a statement that 306 000 winged
animals had so far been culled in 15 of Turkey's 81 provinces. Among
them were the capital Ankara, the country's largest city Istanbul, as
well as remote eastern regions where the disease emerged last month
[December 2005]. Meanwhile, 3 new outbreaks of the disease among fowl
were detected in the west and southeast of the country, according to
local officials quoted by the Anatolia news agency. Slaughtering also
began in the western province of Aydin, where officials reported the
virus among poultry in the popular resort of Kusadasi, on the Aegean
coast facing the Greek island of Samos. Kusadasi is some 1650 km
(1000 miles) from Dogubeyazit, the rural eastern town close to the
Iranian border where the country's 1st flu deaths occurred.
Experts warned the public to be cautious during the 4-day Eid
al-Adha, the Muslim Feast of Sacrifice that began Tuesday [10 Jan
2006] and sees the faithful sacrifice sheep and cows often brought
from rural areas to cities for sale. Although sheep and cattle are
not affected by avian influenza, doctors say animals that have lived
in close proximity with infected poultry could carry the virus on
their skin or hooves.
